00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.360
For more from Kyiv is CBS News reporter Haley Ott.

00:00:03.360 --> 00:00:03.990
Hi, Haley.

00:00:03.990 --> 00:00:06.060
So as you just heard, President Zelensky

00:00:06.060 --> 00:00:08.070
says he wants sanctions on Russia

00:00:08.070 --> 00:00:11.680
to be listed before a possible invasion of Ukraine.

00:00:11.680 --> 00:00:13.320
He wants them as a deterrent.

00:00:13.320 --> 00:00:14.940
What is his reasoning?

00:00:14.940 --> 00:00:18.700


00:00:18.700 --> 00:00:22.800
Well the point President Zelensky made today in Munich

00:00:22.800 --> 00:00:25.740
is one that I've heard echoed by numerous people

00:00:25.740 --> 00:00:28.290
that I've spoken to here in Kyiv during my reporting

00:00:28.290 --> 00:00:29.280
on this story.

00:00:29.280 --> 00:00:33.270
People that I speak to here say that they want a response

00:00:33.270 --> 00:00:36.330
now to Russia's buildup of troops on the Ukrainian border,

00:00:36.330 --> 00:00:38.520
because that buildup in and of itself

00:00:38.520 --> 00:00:42.090
is inflicting damage on the Ukrainian economy.

00:00:42.090 --> 00:00:44.610
There's a huge amount of foreign investment

00:00:44.610 --> 00:00:46.590
in this country that's being pulled out

00:00:46.590 --> 00:00:49.680
because of this crisis, let alone things like tourism.

00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:51.060
Flights have been canceled.

00:00:51.060 --> 00:00:53.400
So people here don't want Russia to be allowed

00:00:53.400 --> 00:00:55.620
to take this kind of action and damage

00:00:55.620 --> 00:00:58.530
the Ukrainian economy in the way that it has been damaged.

00:00:58.530 --> 00:01:00.970
That's the point that President Zelensky made today,

00:01:00.970 --> 00:01:02.640
and that's certainly something that I've

00:01:02.640 --> 00:01:04.500
heard echoed here on the ground by people

00:01:04.500 --> 00:01:05.850
that I've spoken to in Kyiv.

00:01:05.850 --> 00:01:09.270
I mean, seeing that video of President Zelensky speaking,

00:01:09.270 --> 00:01:11.220
there's certainly an urgency to his voice

00:01:11.220 --> 00:01:13.110
that we haven't quite heard before,

00:01:13.110 --> 00:01:15.840
nor from the Ukrainian people.

00:01:15.840 --> 00:01:18.060
So tell us about how that has changed,

00:01:18.060 --> 00:01:20.640
how the sense of urgency has changed among Ukrainians

00:01:20.640 --> 00:01:23.310
where you are, given the latest developments in the Donbass

00:01:23.310 --> 00:01:23.810
region?

00:01:23.810 --> 00:01:27.330


00:01:27.330 --> 00:01:30.870
There has been an uptick in violence, in shelling.

00:01:30.870 --> 00:01:34.080
The Ukrainian military said that two of its forces

00:01:34.080 --> 00:01:36.660
were killed in Eastern Ukraine today.

00:01:36.660 --> 00:01:38.340
Four people were injured.

00:01:38.340 --> 00:01:42.630
That said, people here in the capital city were resolute,

00:01:42.630 --> 00:01:46.170
it seemed, when I spoke to them, about not letting this crisis

00:01:46.170 --> 00:01:48.040
affect their day to day lives.

00:01:48.040 --> 00:01:50.010
I talked to people going to work on a Saturday,

00:01:50.010 --> 00:01:52.770
delivering groceries, going getting their nails done.

00:01:52.770 --> 00:01:54.400
People were out on the streets.

00:01:54.400 --> 00:01:56.400
And they were just living their lives as normal,

00:01:56.400 --> 00:01:59.220
because they say one way that Russia

00:01:59.220 --> 00:02:02.980
could hurt them would be by if they responded to this crisis.

00:02:02.980 --> 00:02:05.100
They said that they're used to dealing with Russia.

00:02:05.100 --> 00:02:06.730
They're used to these kinds of threats.

00:02:06.730 --> 00:02:09.450
And they're going to wait until an invasion actually

00:02:09.450 --> 00:02:11.790
happens, if it does, before they respond.

00:02:11.790 --> 00:02:15.210
That said, some of my colleagues were at the Polish border

00:02:15.210 --> 00:02:18.030
earlier, where people definitely have made moves

00:02:18.030 --> 00:02:20.940
to protect their families potentially

00:02:20.940 --> 00:02:22.450
in case there is an invasion.

00:02:22.450 --> 00:02:24.420
They're staying there for the time being,

00:02:24.420 --> 00:02:27.240
because they think if there's some sort of violence,

00:02:27.240 --> 00:02:29.500
they could cross the border more easily.

00:02:29.500 --> 00:02:33.330
So people are adjusting their lives, because

00:02:33.330 --> 00:02:34.590
of the threat of violence.

00:02:34.590 --> 00:02:37.200
But it's definitely a deliberate thing

00:02:37.200 --> 00:02:40.000
that a lot of people that I've spoken to are doing,

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:42.390
which is saying, we are living our lives as normal.

00:02:42.390 --> 00:02:44.430
We are proceeding as normal.

00:02:44.430 --> 00:02:48.550
Because that is how we can show our own strength.

00:02:48.550 --> 00:02:49.050
All right.

00:02:49.050 --> 00:02:50.400
Well, Haley Ott in Kyiv.

00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:52.400
Thank you so much.